{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17601360","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17601360"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:14:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:14:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15651"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15651","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15651"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.07,0.71,0.02,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8342"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71028"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8342","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8342"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15651"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56499"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7010"},{"type":"tags","id":"8120"},{"type":"tags","id":"10133"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20118"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20120"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71028","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71028"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe adrenal cortex produces several hormones including mineralocorticoids from the zona glomerulosa, glucocorticoids from the zona fasciculata, and androgens from the zona reticularis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a condition caused by excess aldosterone secretion?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hyperkalaemia with metabolic acidosis","Hypotension with sodium wasting","Primary hyperaldosteronism","Secondary adrenal insufficiency","Type 4 renal tubular acidosis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe key effects of aldosterone are to promote sodium retention and potassium excretion in the distal nephron. \u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary hyperaldosteronism\u003C/strong\u003E results from autonomous aldosterone secretion by the adrenal cortex, typically from an adenoma, causing hypertension and hypokalaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyperkalaemia with metabolic acidosis\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the opposite of aldosterone excess, which causes hypokalaemia and metabolic alkalosis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypotension with sodium wasting\u003C/strong\u003E - Aldosterone excess causes sodium retention and hypertension\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESecondary adrenal insufficiency\u003C/strong\u003E - This involves cortisol deficiency due to pituitary dysfunction\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType 4 renal tubular acidosis\u003C/strong\u003E - This is caused by aldosterone deficiency or resistance\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe classic triad of primary hyperaldosteronism includes hypertension, hypokalaemia, and metabolic alkalosis due to increased sodium reabsorption and potassium excretion in the distal tubule and collecting duct.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Primary hyperaldosteronism causes hypertension and hypokalaemia due to excess aldosterone secretion from the adrenal cortex.","Aldosterone acts on the distal tubule and collecting duct to increase sodium reabsorption and potassium excretion.","The clinical features of hyperaldosteronism are opposite to what occurs in aldosterone deficiency."],"references":["Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Wass, J. A., \u0026 Stewart, P. M. (Eds.). (2011). Oxford textbook of endocrinology and diabetes. Oxford University Press, USA","Lotfi CFP, Kremer JL, Dos Santos Passaia B, Cavalcante IP. The human adrenal cortex: growth control and disorders. Clinics (Sao Paulo). 2018 Sep 6;73(suppl 1):e473s. doi: 10.6061/clinics/2018/e473s. PMID: 30208164; PMCID: PMC6113920"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56499"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15651"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56499","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56499"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T19:03:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T19:04:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8342"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71028"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"